SIMPLE: representative
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Representative
<hw>Rep`re*sent"a*tive</hw> <pr>(-z?nt`?-t?v)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[Cf. F. <ets>repr<?/sentatif</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Fitted
to represent; exhibiting a similitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Bearing the character or power of another; acting
for another or others; <as>as, a council <ex>representative</ex> of the
people</as>.</def> <rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Conducted by persons chosen to represent, or act as
deputies for, the people; <as>as, a <ex>representative</ex>
government</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Nat.Hist.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>Serving or
fitted to present the full characters of the type of a group; typical;
<as>as, a <ex>representative</ex> genus in a family</as>.</def>
<sd>(b)</sd> <def>Similar in general appearance, structure, and habits,
but living in different regions; -- said of certain species and
varieties.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Metaph.)</fld> <def>Giving, or existing as, a
transcript of what was originally presentative knowledge; <as>as,
<ex>representative</ex> faculties; <ex>representative</ex>
knowledge</as>. See <er>Presentative</er>, 3 and <er>Represent</er>,
8.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Representative</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Representative
<hw>Rep`re*sent"a*tive</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. LL.
<ets>repraesentativus</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>One who, or that which, represents (anything); that
which exhibits a likeness or similitude.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A statute of Rumor, whispering an idiot in the ear, who was the
<qex>representative</qex> of Credulity.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Difficulty must cumber this doctrine which supposes that the
perfections of God are the <qex>representatives</qex> to us of whatever
we perceive in the creatures.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An agent, deputy, or substitute, who supplies the
place of another, or others, being invested with his or their
authority.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>One who represents, or stands in
the place of, another.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The executor or administrator is ordinarily held to be
the <xex>representative</xex> of a deceased person, and is sometimes
called the <xex>legal representative</xex>, or the <xex>personal
representative</xex>. The heir is sometimes called the <xex>real
representative</xex> of his deceased ancestor. The heirs and executors
or administrators of a deceased person are sometimes compendiously
described as his <xex>real</xex> and <xex>personal
representatives</xex>.</note> <rj><au>Wharton. Burrill.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A member of the lower or popular house in a State
legislature, or in the national Congress.</def> <mark>[U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <fld>(Nat.Hist.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>That which
presents the full character of the type of a group.</def> <sd>(b)</sd>
<def>A species or variety which, in any region, takes the place of a
similar one in another region.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Representatively</ent>⟦br⟧
